) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.grading.rerun',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Re-run asks the AI to grade the same answer again with Sonnet. Use when the initial proposal looks wrong.',
  $$## Re-run (Sonnet)

Re-run submits the same answer and rubric to Stage 2 (Sonnet) again.
Because AI grading is non-deterministic, a second pass sometimes produces
a better proposal, especially for ambiguous answers.

Use re-run when:
- The justification is clearly misaligned with the rubric.
- The anchor hits don't match what you read in the answer.
- The band seems too high or too low but you want a second opinion before
  overriding manually.

Re-run does **not** replace the original proposal — both are in the
`gradings` table (with `override_of` linking them).
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.grading.rerun.opus',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Re-run with Opus (Stage 3) uses a more powerful model. Use for complex cases or appeals.',
  $$## Re-run with Opus (Stage 3)

Stage 3 uses Claude Opus — a more capable but slower model. Use it for:

- Complex multi-step scenario answers where Sonnet's chain-of-thought
  seems shallow.
- Appeals: the candidate disputes the grade and you want an independent
  high-quality re-assessment.
- Calibration: spot-check whether Stage 2 verdicts hold up on a sample
  of high-stakes attempts.

Stage 3 is billed at a higher token cost. The tenant budget guard tracks
and may block if the monthly cap is near.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.grading.skill_drift',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'The prompt version used for this grade differs from the current live prompt. Consider re-grading.',
  $$## Skill drift

Each grading row records the SHA-256 hash of the prompt version that
produced it. If the admin updates a grading skill (prompt template), rows
graded with the old version are flagged with a **drift** badge.

Drift is informational — it does not block releasing results. Use it as a
signal to re-run affected attempts when a prompt change was material (e.g.
a rubric anchor was corrected).
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.scoring.attempt.total',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Sum of earned points across all questions, normalized to 100. Bands are shown per-question only.',
  $$## Total score

The attempt total is a weighted sum of per-question scores, normalized to
100. It is derived from the `attempt_scores` row written when all questions
are graded.

For subjective questions, the per-question score is `reasoning_band × 25`,
so a band-3 answer on a 20-point question contributes 15 points.

The total does **not** drive pass/fail thresholds directly — the archetype
and cohort percentile are also factors. See `admin.scoring.cohort.percentiles`.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.scoring.attempt.archetype',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Behavioral pattern derived from edit count, pace, flags, multi-tab, and copy-paste signals.',
  $$## Archetype signals

The archetype radar charts six behavioral signals collected during the attempt:

| Signal | Measures |
|---|---|
| Pace | Median time per question |
| Edits | Total edit count across answers |
| Flags | Questions flagged for review |
| Focus loss | Tab-blur events |
| Copy/paste | Combined copy + paste events |
| Multi-tab | Multi-tab conflict events |

High edit counts combined with slow pace may indicate careful, deliberate
work. High copy/paste with fast pace may indicate pasted content. Context
matters — interpret signals holistically, not as individual scores.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.scoring.archetype.disclaimer',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Behavioral signals are observational only. They do not affect the score and are not a proxy for integrity.',
  $$## Archetype signal disclaimer

Archetype signals are behavioral telemetry, not integrity flags. They:

- Do **not** adjust the candidate's score in any direction.
- Are **not** a proxy for cheating detection.
- Are context-dependent: a slow pace on L3 scenarios is normal; the same
  pace on an L1 triage question might indicate difficulty.

Use signals to understand cohort patterns (e.g. "L2 candidates average
200 edits per attempt") not to make individual pass/fail decisions.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.scoring.cohort.percentiles',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Rank within the cohort. 90th percentile = scored higher than 90% of candidates on the same assessment.',
  $$## Cohort percentiles

Cohort percentiles are computed once the cohort has ≥5 released results.
They are recomputed on every new release.

A candidate at the 90th percentile scored higher than 90% of the cohort
on the same assessment + level. Percentiles are assessment-scoped — they
do not span across assessments or levels.

Phase 1 computes median and percentile bands (P25, P50, P75, P90). Full
bell-curve distribution charts are a Phase 3 analytics feature.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
