INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.rubric.anchor.weight',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Fractional contribution of this anchor to the total rubric weight. All anchor weights must sum ≤ 1.0.',
  $$## Anchor weight

The weight controls how much this anchor contributes to the overall
scoring floor. All anchor weights must sum to ≤ 1.0 (the UI shows the
running total and blocks saving if exceeded).

Recommended allocation: identify 2–4 *essential* anchors (weight 0.2–0.3
each) and 2–4 *supporting* anchors (weight 0.05–0.1 each). Leave room in
the total so a strong answer that covers most anchors isn't penalized by
one missed nuance.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.rubric.anchor.synonyms',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Comma-separated synonyms or equivalent phrasings the AI should treat as matching the anchor.',
  $$## Anchor synonyms

Add synonyms when the anchor concept has multiple correct phrasings.
Example: anchor phrase "lateral movement", synonyms "east-west traffic,
network pivoting, pivot host".

Synonyms are case-insensitive and matched as substrings within the answer.
Avoid overly broad synonyms that could match unrelated content.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.rubric.anchor.required',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Required anchors must be present for the answer to score above band 0, regardless of overall quality.',
  $$## Required anchor

Marking an anchor **required** creates a hard floor: if the AI does not
detect this concept, the band is capped at 0 regardless of the rest of
the answer quality.

Use sparingly — for concepts so fundamental that their absence represents
a complete misunderstanding. For most anchors, leave required off and let
the holistic band judgement do its work.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.rubric.reasoning.bands',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Band labels and descriptions tell the AI how to distinguish between 0%, 25%, 50%, 75%, and 100%.',
  $$## Reasoning bands

Write a label and description for each of the five bands. These are
included verbatim in the AI grading prompt — they are the specification
the model grades against.

Best practice:
- **Band 4 (100%):** Complete, accurate, specific. Names tools, explains
  tradeoffs, shows system-level reasoning.
- **Band 3 (75%):** Mostly correct. One missing element or weak rationale.
- **Band 2 (50%):** Correct direction, significant gaps. Explains *what*
  but not *why*, or vice versa.
- **Band 1 (25%):** Shows partial understanding. More wrong than right.
- **Band 0 (0%):** No credit. Blank, off-topic, or fundamentally wrong.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.rubric.error_classes',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Error classes tag low-band answers for cohort analytics. Choose the one that best describes the failure.',
  $$## Error classes

Error classes are assigned by the AI when band < 3 and aggregated in the
cohort analytics view. They answer: "what kind of mistake did candidates
make most often on this question?"

Available classes:
- `missing_concept` — the core concept was absent
- `wrong_tool` — candidate chose the wrong approach
- `wrong_reasoning` — reasoning is incorrect despite using the right tool
- `partial_answer` — correct direction, incomplete

Admin overrides can also set the error class. If no class applies, leave
as `none`.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.settings.billing.budget',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Monthly grading run cap per tenant. Default: 100 runs/month. Resets on the 1st of each month.',
  $$## Grading budget cap

The budget guard limits AI grading runs to protect against runaway costs.
A "run" is one call to the grading pipeline per question — a 10-question
attempt uses 10 runs.

Default cap: 100 runs/month per tenant. Contact support to raise the cap.
The `tenant_grading_budgets` table holds the current usage and cap; a
platform admin can edit it directly until Phase 3 ships a settings UI.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.settings.billing.alert_threshold',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Notify the admin when monthly usage exceeds this percentage of the cap (default: 80%).',
  $$## Budget alert threshold

When monthly grading usage crosses this fraction of the cap, AssessIQ sends
an in-app notification and email to all tenant admins. Default: 80%.

The notification is informational — grading continues until the hard cap
is hit. Raise the cap in `tenant_grading_budgets` before that happens.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'admin.settings.help_content.markdown',
  'admin',
  'en',
  'Help text supports Markdown. Preview shows plain text only — full rendering launches in Phase 3.',
  $$## Help content Markdown

Help text bodies accept GitHub-flavored Markdown: headings, bold, italic,
code blocks, ordered/unordered lists, and tables.

The Phase 2 admin editor shows a **plain-text preview** only. Full Markdown
rendering in the editor is deferred to Phase 3. Candidates and admins who
read the help drawer see rendered Markdown via the `HelpProvider` component.

**What to avoid:**
- Raw HTML tags — they are stripped before storage.
- Inline images — not supported in this phase.
- Custom CSS classes — the design system renders Markdown in a sandboxed
  `aiq-prose` container with fixed styles.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'candidate.intro.integrity',
  'candidate',
  'en',
  'AssessIQ measures judgment and reasoning, not memory. Use any reference you would in a real workday.',
  $$## Integrity expectations

This assessment is not a closed-book exam. AssessIQ is built to measure
how you think on the job, not what you can recall under pressure. Use:

- **Documentation** for the tools and languages you would normally
  reference at work.
- **Search engines** to look up syntax or operators.
- **Notes** you would normally have open.

Do **not** ask another person to answer for you, share screens, or paste
answers from another candidate's attempt. AssessIQ records timing
signals, edit patterns, and behavioral fingerprints; identical or
near-identical answers across candidates are flagged for review.

Once you click **Begin Assessment**, the timer starts and cannot be
paused. If your network drops, your answers are saved every 5 seconds —
you can refresh and continue.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'candidate.attempt.timer',
  'candidate',
  'en',
  'Wall-clock time remaining. Auto-submits at zero. Pausing is not supported.',
  $$## Timer

The countdown shows time remaining for the entire assessment, not the
current question. When it reaches zero, AssessIQ auto-submits whatever
answers you have entered.

**The timer keeps running even if you close the tab.** Network dropouts
do not pause it. If you genuinely cannot continue (power outage,
medical emergency), close the tab and contact your administrator
immediately — they can grant a one-time extension before submission.

Behavioral signals recorded by AssessIQ include time spent per question,
number of edits, and navigation pattern. None of these signals affect
your score directly; they inform the admin's review.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'candidate.attempt.flag',
  'candidate',
  'en',
  'Bookmark the question to revisit before final submit. Flags have no scoring impact.',
  $$## Flag for review

Use this when you want to come back to a question before final submission —
for instance, if you are not sure of your answer or want to verify a query.

Flagged questions appear with a star in the navigation panel. You can flag
multiple questions; the **Review** screen lists all flagged + unanswered
items together so you do not miss anything.

Flagging has no scoring impact. It is just a personal bookmark.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'candidate.attempt.kql.editor',
  'candidate',
  'en',
  'Write your KQL query. Syntax highlighting + autocomplete. Press Ctrl+Enter to validate.',
  $$## KQL editor

The editor offers:

- **Syntax highlighting** for KQL keywords, operators, and built-in
  functions.
- **Autocomplete** for table names referenced in the question scenario.
- **Bracket / paren matching** to spot mismatches early.
- **Format on save** (Ctrl+Shift+F) — opinionated, optional.

**Validation** (Ctrl+Enter) checks for:

- Parse errors (red underline).
- Required keyword presence — the question lists tokens that must appear
  somewhere in your query for it to score above band 0.

Validation does not run your query against real data. The grader judges
correctness by combining keyword presence with AI rubric review.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'candidate.attempt.scenario.steps',
  'candidate',
  'en',
  'Multi-step incident. Some steps may unlock only after submitting earlier steps.',
  $$## Scenario steps

Scenario questions describe a developing incident across multiple steps.
Each step asks for a decision or analysis given the evidence so far.

**Two modes:**

- **Free navigation** (default): jump between steps freely. You may
  revise earlier steps as later evidence arrives.
- **Locked progression**: each step unlocks only after you submit the
  previous one. Look for a small lock icon on later steps.

Once you submit a step in locked mode, you cannot edit it. In free mode
every step stays editable until you submit the assessment.

Behavioral note: AssessIQ records the order you visited the steps. There
is no "correct" order — exploring later evidence first is a valid
strategy.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'candidate.attempt.subjective.length',
  'candidate',
  'en',
  'Recommended 80–200 words per answer. Quality of reasoning beats word count.',
  $$## Subjective answer length

Subjective questions are graded on the rubric (anchors and bands), not on
length. A 60-word answer that nails the tradeoff scores higher than a
300-word answer that meanders.

**Rough guide:**

- **Below 40 words:** rarely enough to demonstrate reasoning.
- **80–200 words:** the sweet spot for most rubrics.
- **Above 300 words:** law of diminishing returns; you are using time
  that other questions need.

Markdown formatting (bullets, **bold**, `code`) renders in the grader's
review. Use it when it clarifies; do not use it as filler.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO help_content (id, tenant_id, key, audience, locale, short_text, long_md, version, status)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  NULL,
  'candidate.attempt.disconnect',
  'candidate',
  'en',
  'Your answers autosave every 5 seconds. Refresh and continue — the timer keeps running.',
  $$## If your connection drops

AssessIQ saves your in-progress answers to the server every 5 seconds and
shows a small green check next to "Saved" when the latest save completed.
A red dot means the last save attempt failed; AssessIQ will retry on the
next interval.

**If you lose connectivity:**

1. **The timer keeps running** — wall-clock time, not connected time.
2. **Reconnect and refresh** — your most recent autosaved state loads.
3. **Anything typed during the offline window is lost** — only saved
   state survives a refresh.

For a genuinely-blocking outage (power, hardware failure), close the tab
and contact your administrator. They can grant a one-time extension
before final submission, but cannot extend after auto-submit fires.
$$,
  1,
  'active'
) ON CONFLICT (tenant_id, key, locale, version) DO NOTHING;

